message.content: This is the first Pepe Le Pew cartoon and while similar to later ones, it has some unique aspects. Interestingly, the object of Pepe's affections is a boy cat! This situation arises when a cat, tired of mistreatment, disguises itself as a skunk to be left alone, inadvertently attracting Pepe. Most of the action is typical, but the very funny and unexpected ending makes it one of the best in the series. Excellent animation, different from later styles, combined with great writing and humor, make this a standout cartoon.

Faithful to Burroughs, this movie is excellent; where it departs, it is superb. A tale of family and a father's search by an emotional orphan. Lambert's anguished line, "He was my Father!" can bring tears to the most cynical critic. Not perfect - McDowell's voice overdubbed by Glenn Close is an unconscionable, British error - but a fine, flawed masterpiece and a noble farewell to Sir Ralph Richardson.

Cashing in on the "demons-meets-clergy" trend of the late '60s/early '70s, "The Sentinel" is a noteworthy addition, though often overlooked compared to "Rosemary's Baby," "The Exorcist," and "The Omen." It merges elements of these films with a hint of Polanski's "The Tenant." A New York model struggles with commitment and moves into a seemingly ideal townhouse. She encounters an eccentric neighbor (Burgess Meredith) and odd tenants. Disturbed by noises, she learns only she and a mute priest reside there. Director Michael Winner delivers a supernatural thriller with a devilish twist. A strong cast, subtle plot, and Dick Smith's makeup FX make "The Sentinel" a creepy horror film.

Christophe Lambert once said he was still making movies only to make good and easy money. When I see his latest releases, I can believe that. Beowulf is, all in all, in the "good" part of the crap movies: there are some good thrill scenes, indeed. The actors themselves aren't too bad. But the plot is silly, the "Mortal Kombat"-like music has nothing to do here, the ending is really s****y. Really, the only good thing about it is that me and my friends could laugh about how uninteresting it was. I even wish I wasted my money on something else.

Beowulf is not the kind of movie that leaves a lasting impression. It’s more of a spectacle without substance, where flashy action scenes try to distract from the lack of a coherent storyline. The film tries hard to be entertaining but falls short due to its haphazard script and mismatched soundtrack. Despite the effort from the actors, the movie doesn't manage to elevate itself beyond mediocrity. It’s one of those films that you watch once and quickly forget, except for the moments you chuckle at its absurdity. My friends and I spent more time laughing at its flaws than being engaged by its narrative. In hindsight, spending money on this film felt like a regrettable choice, as there are countless other options that could have offered a more satisfying cinematic experience.

Damon Runyon's attempt to sentimentalize the Mafia gave us "Guys and Dolls," an enduring stage musical adapted into a colorful 1955 film by Joseph L. Mankiewicz. The movie boasts an all-star cast: Vivian Blaine, Jean Simmons (resembling Audrey Hepburn in "Roman Holiday"), Frank Sinatra, and Marlon Brando, both Oscar winners. Brando singing "Luck Be a Lady" hints at early Dylan's vocal style. Stubby Kaye shines as Nicely Nicely Johnson with "Sit Down You're Rocking The Boat," while Sheldon Leonard adds to his rogue gallery. The film's bright, cartoonish look anticipates 1960s Pop Art. Despite dated social attitudes, it's great fun, and even the gentle teasing of the Salvation Army is harmless. Watching Sinatra and Brando together is reason enough to enjoy this 149-minute film.

It seems no matter what I see her in, Christina Ricci seems full of promise but fails to deliver. Sure, she can cry and scream, but Prozac Nation sees Ricci totally out of her depth. Perhaps I'm being too harsh, but okay, I'm shifting the blame to the director. Jessica Lange is outrageous and almost reaches Faye Dunaway heights of megadramatisation. Unfortunately, I think Lange peaked with Frances, and it was all downhill from there. There was every chance of this film being slick and witty while tackling depression head-on. What we get instead is poorly acted hysteria dressed up with a stereotypical try-hard eighties veneer. I really had no sense of the film’s eighties backdrop, as I was unsatisfied with the lame attempt at making believe it was the eighties just because Ms. Ricci wears a Madonna-inspired dress to her "lost my virginity" celebration. Come on, everyone, you are ALL better than this. The filmmakers should hang their heads in shame, and as a result of disappointment, Elizabeth Wurtzel could probably make a bundle if she sued for "irreparable emotional damages" due to the finished product. Go on, Lizzie, sue! I would, because this film not only fails to capture the essence of the book it was based on but also falls flat in delivering any substantial emotional depth or connection. The performances, which had the potential to elevate the material, instead succumb to over-the-top dramatics that feel forced and unconvincing. The direction lacks the subtlety and finesse needed to handle such a complex subject matter. Instead, the film resorts to clichés and superficial portrayals that undermine its intended message. The production design, which attempts to evoke the eighties, comes across as lazy and uninspired, relying on tired tropes and visual clichés rather than creating an authentic sense of time and place. With all these missteps, it’s no wonder that the film fails to resonate on any meaningful level. It’s a missed opportunity that leaves the audience yearning for a more thoughtful and nuanced exploration of its themes.

I've noticed how all the other reviews of this film mention how "wholesome" and "entertaining" it is. These people need to get out of the house more often. I don't know why they're shilling for this vapid, insipid, brainless piece of fluff. Pat Boone has absolutely no acting talent whatsoever, and his ineptness is exceeded only by that of his co-star Pamela Austin, a former model (yet one more reason to outlaw the insidious practice of inflicting talentless models on an unsuspecting moviegoing public, a foul habit that unfortunately persists to this day). A good supporting cast (Terry-Thomas, Edward Everett Horton, among others) tries hard to make some sense out of this, but to no avail. I noticed that two directors shared credit, although "credit" isn't the word I would use (neither is "director"). The film meanders aimlessly from one poorly executed scene to another, leaving the audience bewildered and wondering how such a project ever got greenlit. As for "wholesome entertainment," there are plenty of those types of movies available without torturing your loved ones by forcing them to sit through this. Find one of those films, and skip this one. It’s baffling to think how anyone could label this as something worth watching when there are countless better options around.

This show was a fresh, innovative, and original treat. It makes every other show I've watched look plain boring. From the first episode, I was entranced and became attached to all the characters easily (which rarely happens since I usually dislike some characters). It's a pity there won't be a third season because it's one of the best shows I've ever seen. Nothing can replace Pushing Daisies, as what could ABC find to match this show? It's the best show on television. I came for Kristin Chenoweth and stayed because I fell in love with the entire show.

I LOVE the Doodlebops. My son has been watching them for over a year. We went to their concert last year and yesterday in Connecticut. He LOVES them. The Doodlebops don't teach the alphabet or numbers, but who cares? The TV isn't supposed to teach your children that; parents should. Get over it. The Doodlebops CAN sing. Deedee has a beautiful voice, and in concert, you can tell all three of them have nice voices and don't lip-sync. They dance, jump, and STILL sing. They have talent, and kids love them. I even enjoy watching the show. It's the best kids' show and a rock band for children. How amazing is that? Why are people saying Chad (Rooney) is gay? Whether he is or not, he's awesome! Leave him alone. It's not like anyone is promoting anything to our children!

The saddest thing about this film is that only 8 people cared to leave a review, and no one commented on the message boards. Made the same year as Philadelphia, the Tom Hanks Oscar-winner, this is the film that truly deserved attention and awards. There is more humanity, life, love, tenderness, and beauty in these two people than in almost any other gay film I've seen, and it's all true.

To understand what it was like to be gay in the 60s and 70s and to grasp the reality of AIDS before modern drug "cocktails," this is the film to see. On a personal note, there has been a silver lining to the horror of AIDS. Initially called the "gay cancer," governments ignored it until it affected heterosexuals. The only support available was from gay-established organizations like The Names Project and Act Up. This forced interaction helped break down prejudices, allowing the straight world to accept gays as equals. While many feared increased discrimination, the shared crisis led to significant strides in gay liberation, and acceptance, including gay marriage in several countries. It's tragic that so many had to die, but if this brought us closer, then their deaths were not in vain.
